<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,288,1562,1588]" box="[189,288,1562,1588]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,288,1562,1588]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,288,1562,1588]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ecology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,1608,1776]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">This is a forest species. During the day males rest on tree trunks and rock faces; females, though not exclusively, prefer to hide on the ground in leaf litter and thus are not easy to locate. Consequently, only males have long been known, because they are easier to spot and collect. The species is locally pretty common wherever the daytime microhabitats of females are found. Otherwise, it is readily encountered at night, and this technique revealed large populations in the Mercantour National Park in the French Alps.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
